    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-10-19T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-10-19T22:00:00-05:00" n="486"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d486">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/699: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-10-20T11:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 20, 1927—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 20—10:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>937. Your 358, October 11, 1 p.m. Following from American consul general, Canton:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“October 14, 9 a.m. Your October 7, 6 p.m.<note n="68" xml:id="d486fn68"
                                >See telegram No. 914, Oct. 7, from the Chargé in China, <ref
                                    target="#pg_419">p. 419</ref>.</note> The surtax referred to is
                            the one mentioned in this consulate general’s despatch to <pb
                                facs="0531" n="423" xml:id="pg_423"/> the Legation of October 8,
                                1926,<note n="69" xml:id="d486fn69">
                                <ref target="frus1926v01#pg_873">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1926, vol. <hi
                                        rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 873</ref>.</note> and has never
                            been abolished.</p>
                        <p>The new tax is ten percent of the above tax, the latter in specific
                            instances amounting to two and a half, five, and seven and a half
                            percent.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
